author: By Kelly Weinersmith and Zach Weinersmith
title: Space Billionaires Should Spend More Time Thinking About Sex
description: It’s time to talk about the extraterrestrial birds and the bees.
content: Wherever you are on this planet, you’ve probably given some thought to leaving it. Space is looking more promising every day. There’s no political corruption on Mars, no war on the moon, no juvenile jokes on Uranus.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Ron Lieber and Tara Siegel Bernard
title: Why Banks Are Suddenly Closing Down Customer Accounts
description: Surprised individuals and small-business owners can’t pay rent or make payroll, and no one ever explains what they did wrong.
content: The reasons vary, but the scene that plays out is almost always the same.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Jenna Russell and Amelia Nierenberg
title: After Lewiston Shooting, Maine’s Deaf Community Seeks to Rise Above, Again
description: The attack, in which four of the 18 people killed were Deaf, resurfaced previous traumas and came after decades of efforts to be recognized.
content: As residents across Maine sat riveted to their TVs on Oct. 27, waiting anxiously for updates on the manhunt for a gunman who had killed 18 people, state officials opened their news briefing with a stern directive for the cameras in the room.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Kellen Browning and Nico Grant
title: Another Google Antitrust Battle Reaches Court in Epic Games Case
description: The Fortnite creator accuses Google of stifling app competition, a challenge on top of a federal suit claiming the tech giant abuses its search dominance.
content: For two months, Google has squared off against the Justice Department in court in Washington over claims that the company is abusing its dominant position in online search and advertising to crush rivals, a high-stakes antitrust case that could reshape the world’s most popular search engine. Now, it’s facing another legal challenge closer to home.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Chris Vognar
title: In ‘Lawmen: Bass Reeves,’ Fiction Fills In Where Tall Tales Leave Off
description: The creators of the western drama based on the life of a Black deputy U.S. marshal were inspired by the challenge of filling in the lost history of the famous lawman.
content: Perhaps the best advice ever given in a western came courtesy of a journalist in John Ford’s “The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance”: “When the legend becomes fact, print the legend.” The words ring particularly wise when verifiable facts are scarce, as is the case with the subject of the new series “Lawmen: Bass Reeves” (premiering Sunday on Paramount+).
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Scott Cacciola
title: Tamirat Tola and Hellen Obiri Win New York City Marathon
description: This year’s race saw a course record broken and a dramatically close women’s contest.
content: A decorated women’s field had slowly come unglued over the final few miles of the New York City Marathon on Sunday, to the point where just two runners remained in the hunt for the title.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By The New York Times
title: Tens of thousands rallied in the U.S. in support of Palestinians.
description: In Cincinnati, hundreds clogged a neighborhood once dominated by German immigrants, chanting pro-Palestinian slogans under the watchful eye of police. In San Francisco, thousands filled Civic Center Plaza, many waving Palestinian flags and leaving mementos at an altar to honor those killed in the war in Gaza.
content: In Cincinnati, hundreds clogged a neighborhood once dominated by German immigrants, chanting pro-Palestinian slogans under the watchful eye of police. In San Francisco, thousands filled Civic Center Plaza, many waving Palestinian flags and leaving mementos at an altar to honor those killed in the war in Gaza.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Johnny Diaz
title: Tyson Recalls Nearly 30,000 Pounds of Chicken Nuggets Over Metal Pieces
description: Tyson said it had received complaints from consumers about finding small metal pieces in the product. Federal regulators said one “minor oral injury” had been reported.
content: Tyson Foods is recalling nearly 30,000 pounds of its dinosaur-shaped chicken nuggets after some consumers said they found small metal pieces in them, federal officials said.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Dave Philipps
title: Five Takeaways From a Times Investigation of Artillery Blast Exposure
description: The relentless U.S. artillery bombardment that broke the Islamic State in Syria and Iraq also took a shattering toll on the troops who fired the cannons. Here is what to know.
content: When American military planners launched a ground offensive against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria in 2016, they knew that the American public was weary of long wars in the Middle East, and that the operation would have to make do with very few Americans troops on the ground. So they relied on a strategy that had not been used much in decades: intensive bombardment by heavy artillery.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Nate Cohn
title: Trump Now Leads Biden
description: An analysis of a new set of New York Times / Siena College polls.
content: When Joe Biden ran for president four years ago, he ran as the electability candidate — a broadly appealing, moderate Democrat from Scranton, Pa., who could defeat Donald Trump.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Jennifer Medina
title: Across the Echo Chamber, a Quiet Conversation About War and Race
description: When two acquaintances in Atlanta sat down to find common ground on the Israel-Hamas war, they found themselves in a painful conversation about race, power and whose suffering is recognized.
content: Samara Minkin was already feeling rattled when she saw a Facebook post from one of her children’s former teachers seven days after Hamas killed or kidnapped more than 1,600 people in Israel.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By David W. Chen
title: ‘I’m Not Superwoman’: Philadelphia’s Likely Mayor Urges Teamwork
description: Cherelle Parker, a former City Council member, is poised to become the first woman to lead America’s sixth-biggest city. Her to-do list is daunting.
content: As one urban gardener after another beseeched Cherelle Parker to prevent the green spaces that they had spent years nurturing from being gobbled up by developers, she furiously took notes in her trademark spiral notebook and barely said a word.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Rafael Motamayor
title: ‘Attack on Titan’ Ends How Its Creator Always Envisioned
description: As an anime phenomenon comes to a close, the story’s original creator, Hajime Isayama, breaks down a conclusion that “was pretty much there from the beginning.”
content: This interview contains spoilers for the finale of “Attack on Titan.”
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Jonathan Wolfe
title: Monday Briefing: Antony Blinken Visits the Middle East
description: Plus the rise of space junk.
content: The U.S. secretary of state, Antony Blinken, made an unannounced visit yesterday to Baghdad, showing support for Iraq’s prime minister, Mohammed Shia Al-Sudani, and sending a message to Iran about the Biden administration’s commitment to defending its personnel.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Matthew Mpoke Bigg and Maria Varenikova
title: Russian Strike on Soldiers at Ceremony Was a Crime, Zelensky Says
description: Troops were killed as they gathered in a southern village for a military commemoration, officials said.
content: President Volodymyr Zelensky of Ukraine said Sunday that criminal proceedings had been initiated over an episode in which Russian missiles struck a group of Ukrainian soldiers at an award ceremony in the south of the country, killing some and leaving others wounded.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Patrick Kingsley
title: Israel Quietly Pushed for Egypt to Admit Large Numbers of Gazans
description: The Israeli government has not publicly called for large numbers of Gazans to move to Egypt. But in private, diplomats say, it has pushed for just that — augmenting Palestinian fears of a permanent expulsion.
content: Israel has quietly tried to build international support in recent weeks for the transfer of several hundred thousand civilians from Gaza to Egypt for the duration of its war in the territory, according to six senior foreign diplomats.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By John Branch and Jim Wilson
title: What the Golden Gate Is (Finally) Doing About Suicides
description: After years of pressure from victims’ families, the installation of $217 million in steel netting is almost complete.
content: It was May 27, 1937, the opening day for a stunning new suspension bridge across a gap in the California coastline known as the Golden Gate. Before cars were allowed on the crossing, an estimated 200,000 people celebrated between the bridge’s four-foot-high rails, more than 200 feet above the water.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By The Learning Network
title: What’s Going On in This Picture? | Nov. 6, 2023
description: Look closely at this image, stripped of its caption, and join the moderated conversation about what you and other students see.
content: 1. After looking closely at the image above (or at the full-size image), think about these three questions:
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Hiba Yazbek and Samar Abu Elouf
title: Explosion Gazans Say Was Airstrike Leaves Many Casualties in Dense Neighborhood
description: Dozens were taken to nearby Al-Aqsa Martyrs Hospital, where a photographer for The New York Times saw the injured crowding the hallways and the lifeless being prepared for burial.
content: An explosion overnight in a densely populated part of the central Gaza Strip destroyed several buildings and appeared to have killed and wounded many people, photos and videos from the scene on Sunday showed.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Ruth Graham
title: ‘Like Winning the Lottery’: Mike Johnson’s Ascent Excites Conservative Christians
description: The new speaker of the House is a Southern Baptist who embodies evangelical beliefs and priorities, with a long history of work against abortion and gay rights.
content: Two days after the Supreme Court overturned Roe v. Wade last year, a little-known congressman named Mike Johnson took the stage at Christian Center Shreveport to celebrate.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Nate Cohn and Alicia Parlapiano
title: Why Biden Is Behind, and How He Could Come Back
description: A polling deficit against Trump across six key states is mainly about younger, nonwhite and less engaged voters. Kamala Harris performs slightly better.
content: Four years ago, Joe Biden was the electability candidate — the broadly appealing, moderate Democrat from Scranton who promised to win the white working-class voters who elected Donald J. Trump.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Clyde Haberman
title: His Mother Spoke Truth to Power, Until She Was Killed for It
description: Daphne Caruana Galizia devoted her life to exposing Malta’s pervasive corruption, writes her son, the journalist Paul Caruana Galizia, in “A Death in Malta.”
content: Daphne Caruana Galizia was both famous and infamous in Malta, an in-your-face journalist who wrote that “the greatest enemy of freedom of expression” is fear, for it leads to “the dangerous situation where individuals are gagged.” Being gagged was the last thing Caruana Galizia could tolerate. Ultimately, fearlessness got her killed.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Alyson Krueger
title: How a Century-Old Jewish Fire Brigade Processes Grief Over the War
description: The Ner Tamid Society within the New York Fire Department is growing for the first time in decades. Members say its purpose has taken on new urgency.
content: When the news broke on Oct. 7 that Hamas had attacked Israel, members of the Ner Tamid Society, a fraternal organization for Jewish employees of the New York Fire Department, immediately reached out to one another to process the news.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By New York Times Games
title: The Connections Companion
description: In case you need some puzzle help.
content: Good morning, dear connectors. Welcome to today’s Connections forum, where you can give and receive puzzle — and emotional — support.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Nadav Gavrielov
title: An Israeli runner mourns members of his run club.
description: Yaniv Zaguri skipped a run with his club on Oct. 7 because he was tired from training for the marathon. Two members who went were killed by Hamas.
content: Yaniv Zaguri, an Israeli athlete, was so tired from a 22-mile run that was part of his training for the New York City Marathon that he decided to skip an early morning run with his club, the Sderot Front Runners, on Oct. 7.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Melissa Eddy
title: Job Action Against Tesla Puts Sweden’s Unions in Spotlight
description: The automaker’s mechanics in Sweden are striking for a collective agreement, and dockworkers say they will support the battle. Tesla is expected to join the talks on Monday.
content: More than a week after Tesla mechanics in Sweden began a strike to compel the U.S. automaker to accept a collective labor agreement, union officials said Tesla representatives would meet with the union on Monday.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By New York Times Games
title: Today’s Wordle Review
description: In case you need some puzzle help.
content: Welcome to The Wordle Review. Be warned: This page contains spoilers for today’s puzzle. Solve Wordle first, or scroll at your own risk.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Katie Robertson and Benjamin Mullin
title: Will Lewis Named C.E.O. of the Washington Post
description: The former Dow Jones executive most recently co-founded The News Movement, a start-up aimed at young audiences.
content: Will Lewis, the former Dow Jones chief executive and publisher of The Wall Street Journal, will be the next chief executive of The Washington Post.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Joshua Barone
title: Review: Anthony Davis’s Malcolm X Opera Finally Arrives at the Met
description: “X: The Life and Times of Malcolm X,” from 1986, receives its grandest treatment yet, in a production expected to play on opera stages from coast to coast.
content: The epigraph of Anthony Davis’s opera “X: The Life and Times of Malcolm X” is a quote from an interview in which, asked about the cost of freedom, Malcolm responds, “The cost of freedom is death.”
source.name: The New York Times

title: Have a Question About the Times/Siena 2024 Poll? Ask It Here
description: Times reporters will answer readers’ questions about new polling on next year’s presidential race.
content: New polling by The New York Times and Siena College finds former President Donald J. Trump leading President Biden in five of six crucial swing states one year ahead of the 2024 presidential election.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Michael D. Shear
title: Democrats Express Deep Anxiety as Polls Show Biden Trailing Trump
description: President Biden’s team emphasized that polls have failed to predict the results of elections when taken a year ahead of time.
content: White House officials on Sunday shrugged off weekend polling that showed President Biden trailing former President Donald J. Trump, even as Democrats said they were increasingly worried about Mr. Biden’s chances in 2024.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Winston Choi-Schagrin and Dave Sanders
title: Living in a Neighborhood That Floods, Rain or Shine
description: As high tide floods increase in some areas of New York City, its residents are asking themselves: When does a place become unlivable?
content: On a cloudless morning two years ago, shortly after Danielle Smith moved into a new apartment in Far Rockaway, Queens, she looked out of her window and saw a swan gliding by.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Bhadra Sharma and Mujib Mashal
title: Deadly Quake in Nepal Renews Fears of an Even Deadlier One
description: The Himalayan country is far behind in enforcing construction codes despite sitting on the fault lines of two major tectonic plates, experts say.
content: Officials in Nepal were still assessing the extent of the damage on Sunday from the earthquake that struck the country’s west two nights earlier, leaving at least 150 people dead and thousands either homeless or afraid to sleep indoors.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Nadav Gavrielov
title: Garth Barfoot, 87, Is the Oldest Runner in the New York City Marathon
description: Barfoot, of New Zealand, says he has run dozens of marathons, but this is his first time running New York’s.
content: Garth Barfoot’s training regimen has been fairly straightforward: daily runs to his favorite coffee shop and back home.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Ken Belson
title: Marcel Hug and Catherine Debrunner Win Marathon’s Wheelchair Races
description: Marcel Hug won his record sixth New York City Marathon while Catherine Debrunner won her debut and set a course record.
content: Marcel Hug and Catherine Debrunner, both from Switzerland, won the men’s and women’s wheelchair races in the New York City Marathon on Sunday. Hug won a record sixth victory on New York’s course, while Debrunner set a course record in her debut in the race.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Julian E. Barnes
title: C.I.A. Director Visits Israel and the Middle East Amid Israel-Hamas War
description: William J. Burns’s visit comes as the United States tries to prod Israel to pursue a more targeted approach to attacking Hamas, allow pauses in the fighting and do more to avoid civilian casualties.
content: William J. Burns, the C.I.A. director, arrived in Israel on Sunday for discussions with leaders and intelligence officials, the first stop in a multicountry trip in the region, according to U.S. officials.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Ian Leslie
title: ‘Now and Then, I Miss You’: The Love Story at the Heart of the Last Beatles Song
description: Almost everything John Lennon and Paul McCartney felt — and they felt a lot — was poured into their music.
content: Sixty-one years after releasing their first single, “Love Me Do,” the Beatles have released their last. “Now and Then” mirrors, in the three beats of its title, its antecedent, which is on the other side. The single accompanies a new version of the group’s Red and Blue greatest hits albums.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Sam Corbin
title: Towel Holders
description: Desirée Penner and Jeff Sinnock make their New York Times debut.
content: Jump to: Today’s Theme | Tricky Clues
source.name: The New York Times

author: By New York Times Games
title: Spelling Bee Forum
description: Feeling stuck on today’s puzzle? We can help.
content: SUNDAY — Hi busy bees! Welcome to today’s Spelling Bee forum. There are a number of terms that appear in both this article and other online discussions of the Spelling Bee; a glossary of those terms compiled by Monicat, a Times reader, can be found below.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Alexis Soloski
title: ‘For All Mankind’ Launches a Mission to Mars, With New Wrinkles
description: For a show that has aged its characters over many decades, the biggest challenge is not sending people to Mars but making them look believable once they arrive.
content: When Ed Baldwin lands on the moon in October 1971, he is in early middle age. His light brown hair swoops across his forehead. His clean-shaven face is ruddy and, excepting a divot between his eyebrows, unwrinkled. But space can really age a man. By 2003, on Mars, his hair has grayed and receded, and the wrinkles have multiplied and deepened. His skin is sallow, marked with age spots. His cheeks have sunk in.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Jaime Green
title: Befouling the Final Frontier
description: As humanity rushes back to space, we seem to be repeating some of the mistakes we’ve made on Earth.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Kyle Buchanan
title: With ‘Dream Scenario,’ Nicolas Cage Reclaims the Memes
description: In his new dark comedy, the star plays a man who begins popping up in people’s dreams. It’s a metaphor for viral fame that he found cathartic.
content: Nicolas Cage is not afraid to go big. This is, after all, a man who channeled the grandiose gestural acting of German expressionist films while starring in “Moonstruck” and was nearly fired from “Peggy Sue Got Married” for using a voice he had modeled on the Claymation sidekick Pokey from “Gumby.” Even the decision to change his name — born Nicolas Coppola, he traded his filmmaking family’s famous moniker for the comic-book superhero Luke Cage’s — allowed him to invent a personal mythology in line with his outsize ambitions.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By David N. Hackney
title: Abortion Rights Have Been Winning. Ohio Leaders Are Trying to Change That.
description: Tuesday’s election on an abortion-related ballot initiative could have consequences beyond the state.
content: By Nov. 7, my fellow Ohioans will cast votes on Issue 1, a ballot initiative that would secure access to reproductive health care, including abortion. It is the only statewide election specifically about reproductive rights in 2023. Whichever way the vote goes, both sides of the debate are likely to draw lessons about abortion-related strategy for next year, when several more ballot initiatives are expected.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Andrew E. Kramer
title: ‘I Am Dreaming It Will Stop’: A Deadlocked War Tests Ukrainian Morale
description: Pessimism over prospects for a quick victory is increasing, and the spirit that infused the first days of the conflict is starting to fade, polls find.
content: Listening to the daily thud of artillery hitting nearby towns, a school principal in southern Ukraine appealed to parents for donations for a new bomb shelter.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Robert Kolker, Jack D'Isidoro, Aaron Esposito, John Woo, Sophia Lanman and Devin Murphy
title: The Sunday Read: ‘The Botched Hunt for the Gilgo Beach Killer’
description: For 13 years, the police failed to scrutinize the man now accused of the infamous murders. Why did it take so long?
content: The beginning of the story was strangely familiar, like the opening scene in a shopworn police procedural: A woman runs screaming down a street in Oak Beach, a secluded gated community on Long Island’s South Shore, only to vanish, it seems, into thin air. It was almost dawn on May 1, 2010. Hours earlier, Shannan Gilbert traveled from New Jersey to see a man who had hired her as an escort from a Craigslist ad. By the time the police arrived, she was gone. They talked to the neighbors, the john and her driver and came up with nothing. A few days later, they ordered a flyover of the area and, again, saw no sign of her. Then they essentially threw up their hands. She went into the ocean, they decided, either hysterical or on drugs.
source.name: The New York Times

title: ‘At One Point, I Took a Step, and the Book Fell Out of My Hands’
description: A paperback rescued from the tracks, living out a Macy’s fantasy and more reader tales of New York City in this week’s Metropolitan Diary.
content: Dear Diary:
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Alana Zeitchik
title: Six Members of My Family Are Hostages in Gaza. Does Anyone Care?
description: It seems the left has a hard time holding space for both Jewish and Palestinian civilians.
content: On Oct. 24 my brother and I went to the United Nations to watch an emergency Security Council meeting in response to the war in Israel and Gaza. As the Israeli minister of foreign affairs listed the names and held up photos of some of the Israeli children who were taken hostage by Hamas, a white woman in her 30s stood up near us in the gallery to protest. She held up a handmade “Free Palestine” sign.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By David French
title: ‘MAGA Mike Johnson’ and Our Broken Christian Politics
description: The speaker needs to consult his Bible more carefully.
content: There are two moments from Mike Johnson’s early days as speaker of the House that almost perfectly encapsulate the broken way that so many Republican evangelicals approach politics. The first occurred just after the House elected Johnson. ABC’s Rachel Scott started to ask Johnson about his efforts to overturn the 2020 election. But before she could finish, Johnson’s Republican colleagues started to shout her down. Johnson simply shook his head. “Next question,” he said, as if the query wasn’t worth his time. It was the kind of conduct that led the Florida Republican Matt Gaetz to dub the new speaker “MAGA Mike Johnson.”
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Callie Holtermann and Hilary Swift
title: Forget Aerodynamics: Running the Marathon in Style
description: “Joy and performance are not mutually exclusive,” said Alexi Pappas. She was one of many runners standing out at the starting line of the New York City Marathon.
content: As 7 a.m. approached on Sunday, a crowd of runners stumbled blearily off the Staten Island Ferry in fleece blankets and body glitter. The blankets were for warmth, and the body glitter for morale to help them through the 26.2 miles that lay ahead.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Claire Fahy
title: These Are the Celebrities Who Ran in the New York Marathon
description: Sheinelle Jones of the “Today” show, the actress Patina Miller and Matt James of “The Bachelor” were among the notable names participating.
content: The celebrities registered to run in this year’s marathon may not all be A-listers, but that doesn’t stop everyone else from comparing their times.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By David C. Adams
title: A Chance Encounter and a Fugitive Linked to a President’s Killing Is Caught
description: A top Haitian police official was grocery shopping when he recognized another customer: a man wanted for questioning in the assassination of President Jovenel Moïse.
content: A senior Haitian police official was shopping at his local supermarket on a recent weekday when someone caught his eye: the country’s most wanted man.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Sarah Diamond
title: A Word That’s True to Its Core
description: “Core” defines the center of something. But it also wears an aesthetic meaning.
content: The summer of 2023 was painted pink. The “Barbie” movie broke records at the box office and inspired “Barbiecore,” an aesthetic “made up primarily of hot pink, and similarly bold rosy hues like fuchsia and magenta,” according to a New York Times article about the rise of Barbie-inspired home décor. “Everything I buy is always a little bit Barbie-esque,” said a homeowner who had outfitted her backyard with a hot-pink aboveground pool and shimmery floats.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Emma Bubola
title: French Nuns and Climate Activists Square Off Over Plans for a Megachurch
description: A yearslong standoff over an enormous church complex in a natural park recently broke out in clashes, when the nuns gave chase.
content: When climate activists protesting the building of a huge church complex in a natural park in the South of France scaled the construction site, the nuns gave chase.
source.name: The New York Times

title: Student and Teacher, Moving Up Together
description: Readers respond to an essay by Adam Grant. Also: Trump lackeys; not true “conservatives"; saving the New York skyline.
content: To the Editor:
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Sam Sifton
title: Chaat Party Has Entered the Party Chat
description: It’s the sort of tangy, sweet, fiery and crunchy dish you want to assemble rather than cook after a busy day.
content: Good morning. We were out on the water last weekend, chasing striped bass in the Lower Bay south of the Verrazzano-Narrows Bridge; along Midland Beach on Staten Island; at Sandy Hook and Romer Shoal in New Jersey; off Breezy Point, in Queens, then east along the Rockaway Peninsula to the beach club we call the Cabanas and finally back into Jamaica Bay.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Shane Goldmacher, Nicholas Nehamas and Maggie Haberman
title: Kim Reynolds, Iowa’s Influential Governor, Expected to Endorse DeSantis
description: The move is a big win for the Florida governor — and a snub to Donald Trump — just months before the Iowa caucuses.
content: Gov. Kim Reynolds of Iowa is expected to endorse Gov. Ron DeSantis of Florida in the Republican presidential primary on Monday, throwing her significant clout in the state behind him as he tries to make up ground against former President Donald J. Trump before the state’s caucuses in January.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Hannah Beech, Muktita Suhartono and Ryn Jirenuwat
title: Half a World Away, Thais Pray for Loved Ones Caught in Hamas Attacks
description: Dozens of migrant farm workers were seized or killed in the Oct. 7 raids on Israel, and their relatives are pleading for answers: “We have nothing to do with their war.”
content: She does not know why they are fighting in the Holy Land halfway across the world, or even exactly who is fighting. All she wants is her son to come home.
source.name: The New York Times

title: Quotation of the Day: An Old-Fashioned With a Twist: It’s Made With Brandy
description: Quotation of the Day for Sunday, November 5, 2023.
content: “It’s always bourbon. It’s always been bourbon. It’ll always be bourbon.”
source.name: The New York Times

title: Images from today’s race so far.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Edward Wong and Patrick Kingsley
title: U.S. Officials Fear American Guns Ordered by Israel Could Fuel West Bank Violence
description: Israel wants 24,000 assault rifles. Itamar Ben-Gvir, a far-right minister overseeing the police, has given rifles to civilians and is forming “security squads.”
content: An Israeli government request for 24,000 assault rifles from the United States is drawing scrutiny from American lawmakers and some State Department officials who fear the weapons might end up in the hands of settlers and civilian militias trying to force Palestinians from land in the West Bank, where violence has been surging, U.S. officials say.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Ben Protess, Jonah E. Bromwich and Maggie Haberman
title: Trump’s Credibility, Coherence and Control Face Test on Witness Stand
description: The former president will testify Monday in a trial that threatens the business empire that created his public persona. He will be out of his element and under oath.
content: Donald J. Trump took the rally stage on a scorching August day in New Hampshire, a political shark, brazen and sly, as he ridiculed his legal opponents as “racist” and “deranged.”
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Shane Goldmacher
title: Trump Leads in 5 Critical States as Voters Blast Biden, Times/Siena Poll Finds
description: Voters in battleground states said they trusted Donald J. Trump over President Biden on the economy, foreign policy and immigration, as Mr. Biden’s multiracial base shows signs of fraying.
content: President Biden is trailing Donald J. Trump in five of the six most important battleground states one year before the 2024 election, suffering from enormous doubts about his age and deep dissatisfaction over his handling of the economy and a host of other issues, new polls by The New York Times and Siena College have found.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Andrew Meier
title: The ‘Picnic’ That Brought Down the Iron Curtain
description: Matthew Longo’s new book details how ordinary citizens helped speed the downfall of the Soviet empire.
content: “Gorbachev will pay for his sins! I can’t stand the sight of his pig’s mug!” On a winter day early in 2001, Grigori Romanov, once the party boss of Leningrad and an odds-on favorite to take over the Kremlin, stood on a Moscow sidewalk ranting to me, a Moscow correspondent for Time magazine, about Mikhail Gorbachev.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Orlando Mayorquin
title: This Ancient Sea Creature Prowled the Waters Over North Dakota
description: Researchers said they had discovered a new line of mosasaur, a giant sea-dwelling creature that lived alongside the dinosaurs. Its name, Jormungandr walhallaensis, draws on Norse mythology.
content: In Norse mythology, a monstrous sea serpent wrapped itself around the world’s waters. Its name was Jormungandr.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Erin Nolan
title: How much prize money will the winners get?
description: Nearly $900,000 will be awarded to the top finishers of the New York City Marathon, with the winners of the elite men’s and women’s divisions receiving $100,000 each.
content: Nearly $900,000 is guaranteed to be awarded to the top finishers in this year’s New York City Marathon, and additional prize money could be distributed if athletes break course records.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Richard Sandomir
title: Walter Davis, Basketball Star With a Velvet Touch, Dies at 69
description: “Walter is a good shooter until the fourth period,” one coach said of Davis, a standout in both college and the N.B.A. “Then he becomes a great shooter.”
content: Walter Davis, whose smooth shooting propelled him to basketball stardom with the University of North Carolina and the Phoenix Suns, but who late in his career struggled with drug addiction, died on Thursday while visiting family in Charlotte, N.C. He was 69.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Dave Philipps and Matthew Callahan
title: A Secret War, Strange New Wounds and Silence From the Pentagon
description: Many U.S. troops who fired vast numbers of artillery rounds against the Islamic State developed mysterious, life-shattering mental and physical problems. But the military struggled to understand what was wrong.
content: When Javier Ortiz came home from a secret mission in Syria, the ghost of a dead girl appeared to him in his kitchen. She was pale and covered in chalky dust, as if hit by an explosion, and her eyes stared at him with a glare as dark and heavy as oil.
source.name: The New York Times

title: Corrections: Nov. 5, 2023
description: Corrections that appeared in print on Sunday, Nov. 5, 2023.
content: An article on Page 16 this weekend about the singer-songwriter Kirsty MacColl misstates the name of a folk singer. She is Norma Waterson, not Nora Watterson.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By Clyde McGrady
title: When Tim Scott Tried to Appeal to Black Voters, and Lost
description: The Republican presidential candidate’s defeat in a largely Black South Carolina district in 1996 derailed his promise as someone who could expand the party’s appeal.
content: On a balmy, overcast October afternoon in South Carolina, Tim Scott, the state’s junior senator and current Republican presidential hopeful, worked his way from the back of the Corner Perk Brunch Cafe to a makeshift stage at the front of the crowded room. He stopped to hug and greet adoring supporters in his path. Mr. Scott, who grew up idolizing professional wrestlers, looked the part of the fan favorite on his way to the ring.
source.name: The New York Times

author: By The New York Times
title: Blinken Visits Iraq in Hopes of Containing Israel-Hamas War
description: Amid concerns that the conflict in Gaza could spill across the Middle East, the U.S. secretary of state, Antony J. Blinken, met with Iraqi officials and U.S. personnel to reaffirm the United States’ commitment to protecting its partners.
